{{advert|date=January 2013}} '''CaseMap''' was introduced 1998 as [[relational database]] [[software]] for law offices to store and retrieve [[evidence]] and sources of evidence in litigation. It includes [[Table (database)|database table]]s (the program's documentation refers to them as ''spreadsheets'') for facts, issues, documents, [[physical evidence]], [[deposition (law)|deposition]]s, [[pleading]]s, persons, organizations, places, and other types of data. The program's documentation refers to these types of data as ''objects''. Using the program involves linking the various sources of evidence (e.g., documents, [[deposition (law)|deposition]]s, and persons) to facts that are relevant in the case and to the issues to be decided in the case. The facts table can be sorted by date to provide a chronology of facts.<ref>{{cite news | last = Kennedy | first = Dennis | title = Revolutionizing Case Preparation and Client Relations with CaseMap 5—Making It Easier to Win Cases and Clients | work = Law Practice Today | pages = | publisher = American Bar Association | date = November 2004 | url = http://www.abanet.org/lpm/lpt/articles/tch11041.html | accessdate = 2008-05-11}}</ref>
The use of large volumes of [[digital evidence]] and [[e-discovery]] in modern litigation has led law offices to increase their use of litigation support programs such as CaseMap.<ref>{{cite news | last = Kennedy | first = Dennis | coauthors = | title = Legal Technology Predictions for 2005: Color My World | work = Law Practice Today | pages = | publisher = American Bar Association | date = January 2005 | url = http://www.abanet.org/lpm/lpt/articles/tch01051.html | accessdate = 2008-05-11}}</ref>
CaseMap is owned by [[LexisNexis]]. The current version is CaseMap 13.
